for _ in range(n)] for _ in range(m)]\n        \n        for i in range(m):\n            for j in range(n):\n                if mat[i][j] == 1:\n                    # Horizontal\n                    dp[i][j][0] = dp[i][j-1][0] + 1 if j > 0 else 1\n                    # Vertical\n                    dp[i][j][1] = dp[i-1][j][1] + 1 if i > 0 else 1\n                    # Diagonal\n                    dp[i][j][2] = dp[i-1][j-1][2] + 1 if i > 0 and j > 0 else 1\n                    # Anti-diagonal\n                    dp[i][j][3] = dp[i-1][j+1][3] + 1 if i > 0 and j < n - 1 else 1\n                    \n                    # Update the maximum length found\n                    max_length = max(max_length, dp[i][j][0], dp[i][j][1], dp[i][j][2], dp[i][j][3])\n        \n        return max_length\n```\n\nThis solution uses dynamic programming to keep track of the longest line of consecutive ones in four possible directions (horizontal, vertical, diagonal, and anti-diagonal) for each cell in the matrix. The `dp` array is a 3D array where `dp[i][j][k]` represents the length of the longest line of consecutive ones ending at cell `(i, j)` in the `k`-th direction. The final result is the maximum value found in the `dp` array.", "estimated_date": 1438905600000}